Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ & became obsessed. So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world. Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this travel vlog to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with this lifestyle and did everything we could to keep going. 4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time. Who are Kara and Nate?! 
Watch our documentary here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FuFv4iF8wgg&t=1s 

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are in our 9TH YEAR of finding the best adventures the world has to offer :) 

We are incredibly grateful to be able to continue doing something we love every day. ğŸ˜ŠğŸ¥ğŸŒ Thank you to everyone who has been a part of our journey!

Who are Kara and Nate?!

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are in our 9TH YEAR of finding the best adventures the world has to offer :) 

We are incredibly grateful to be able to continue doing something we love every day. ğŸ˜ŠğŸ¥ğŸŒ Thank you to everyone who has been a part of our journey!

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are in our 9TH YEAR of finding the best adventures the world has to offer :)

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are in our 9TH YEAR of finding the best adventures the world has to offer :) 

We are incredibly grateful to be able to continue doing something we love every day. ğŸ˜ŠğŸ¥ğŸŒ Thank you to everyone who has been a part of our journey!

#vanlife / #Travel #vlog 735 | Utah, USA | Filmed October 2020

If you want to try the curry I made in this episode, here are some more detailed instructions! This recipe will feed ~4 people, depending on how hungry they are ;) Have fun with it!

Like I said in the video, my sister-in-law showed me this recipe, but here is the original!!: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jaN3qsqXt38

What youâ€™ll need, in order: (I tweaked it from the OG a little bit)
6-8 garlic cloves (depending on your taste ;))
1 onion
1 fresh ginger ~2 inches minced
(+ any other vegetable you enjoy!)
Olive oil
Turmeric powder
Curry powder
Red Pepper Flakes
Salt & pepper
â€”
2 cans of chickpeas
1 can of coconut milk
1 can of broth
â€”
Basamati rice
1 bunch of greens
1 bunch of fresh cilantro
1 scoop of plain greek yogurt 

1. Chop garlic, onion, and ginger, and sautÃ© them in olive oil with salt and pepper and sizzle until a little brown - maybe takes my tiny burner about 10 min. 
    1. Add in any other vegetables youâ€™d like here! I have used sweet potatoes, regular potatoes, zucchini, bell pepperâ€¦there are no rules!
2. While those are cooking, drain and rinse chickpeas.
    1. Add them in with the ginger garlic mixture
3. Stir everything up, and add in the turmeric, curry powder, more salt and pepper, and any other spice that tickles your fancy.
    1. Let this cook for a few more minutes with with minimal stirring, browning chickpeas.
    2. Once chickpeas are done, mash them up a little to help thicken the curry.
4. Next, pour in the can of coconut milk. 
5. Right after that, fill that same coconut milk can up with the broth and pour. Or just buy a can of broth and use that, but itâ€™s nice to have the bigger jug incase you want to add more later. Stir!
6. This where I sprinkle in some red pepper flakes to add some heat!
7. Bring to a small boil and just walk away! Let it alllll sizzle and thicken on medium heat until itâ€™s to a nice thick consistency. Maybe 20 minutes.
8. While itâ€™s thickening, make the rice. 
9. Right before the curry is done, throw in some spinach, or whatever green you like. I actually think chopped kale is the best. Stir and let them cook in the soup for the last couple minutes. 
10. Once itâ€™s ready, serve the curry over rice, and add the best parts on top:
    1. 1 scoop of greek yogurt
    2. A [giant handful of] chopped fresh cilantro
    3. A shake of turmeric powder just because itâ€™s pretty :)
    4. Drizzle olive oil. Enjoy!

title: WE LIVED IN THE SINGAPORE AIRPORT (flying to our 99th country!)
description:
We lived in the Singapore Airport Jewel for 3 days - Could you do it?

There was no easy way to get from Bhutan to our 99th country of Vanuatu, so we flew from Paro to Singapore for a LONG layover and decided the most efficient use of our time to work would be to just stay at the airport! So we did not leave until our next flight left 55 hours later, but staying in the recent $1.3 billion addition called the Jewel wasn't so bad ;)

title: We Visited the Most Remote Town in Australia
description:
We drove a truck camper drove over 1,000 km through the Outback to Australiaâ€™s most remote town! (part 1) Go to our sponsor https://betterhelp.com/kandn for 10% off your first month of therapy with BetterHelp and get matched with a therapist who will listen and help :) 

Watch PART 2 here!! - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OZ9cpQ1PWBU 

We rented our car through Adventure Rentals! Check them out: https://adventurerentals.com.au/?utm_medium=youtube_source=karaandnateyoutube_campaign=karaandnate

*PLEASE read the details below if you are planning your own roadtrip here* :) 
Aboriginal held land in Australia is private property and to travel through, you need permission often in the form of a permit. For Kiwirrkurra Country,Â a permit allows you to travel along the main road, into community and camp at approved campsites. Access into any other areas aside from this is still prohibited. More information on traveling through Kiwirrkurra country can be found atÂ https://www.tjamutjamu.com/travelling-to-kiwirrkurra-countryÂ andÂ https://kiwirrkurra.au/. The Kiwirrkurra Traditional Owners thank you for respecting their culture and country.

ALSO! If you are looking to buy Aboriginal art, make sure you buy from the most ethical sources which are community artist-owned art galleries and collectives. For Kiwirrkurra art you can purchase through Papunya Tula Artists (https://papunyatula.com.au/). For other Central Australian Aboriginal art, visit Desart for more information atÂ https://desart.com.au/ Thank you :)

title: We Slept on Bangladesh's 100 Year Old Cruise Ship (full tour)
description:
We paid $26 to sleep in a First Class Cabin on Bangladesh's 100 year old "Rocket Paddle Steamer"! Would you do it?

We are currently in our 97th country of Bangladesh, and after spending our first 2 days in the crazy city of Dhaka, we boarded this 100 year old ship to sail overnight to Barisal. Paddle steamers have been traveling Bangladeshâ€™s rivers since the early 1900s, but today there are only 3 left in service. The river is filled with hundreds of modern ferries that are faster and more comfortable, but tonightâ€™s journey isnâ€™t about the speed or the comfort, itâ€™s about experiencing a way of travel that has remained unchanged for almost 100 years!

title: Floating in the DEAD SEA! UNREAL Experience
description:
Floating in the Dead Sea is an incredible experience. It is literally impossible to sink, and it's the craziest feeling! We spent the whole day bathing in the mineral rich mud, floating in the crazy salty water, and soaking in hot Dead Sea baths (where I actually almost fell asleep WHILE FLOATING IN WATER?!). Who are Kara and Nate?!

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are in our 9TH YEAR of finding the best adventures the world has to offer :) 

We are incredibly grateful to be able to continue doing something we love every day. ğŸ˜ŠğŸ¥ğŸŒ Thank you to everyone who has been a part of our journey!

Who are Kara and Nate?! 
Watch our documentary here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FuFv4iF8wgg&t=1s

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this travel vlog to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time.

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are finding the best adventures the world has to offer :) 

We are incredibly grateful to be able to continue doing something we love every day. ğŸ˜ŠğŸ¥ğŸŒ Thank you to everyone who has been a part of our journey!

Who are Kara and Nate?! 
Watch our documentary here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FuFv4iF8wgg&t=1s 

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are in our 9TH YEAR of finding the best adventures the world has to offer :) 

We are incredibly grateful to be able to continue doing something we love every day. ğŸ˜ŠğŸ¥ğŸŒ Thank you to everyone who has been a part of our journey!

title: JERUSALEM, ISRAEL'S OLD CITY (not what we expected)
description:
Jerusalem is a place we have known about since before we can remember. It was a surreal experience walking the streets of the Old Town today, but it was also emotionally draining for many reasons. We explored as much as possible in one day including the Temple Mount, the Western Wall, Via Dolorosa, the Church of the Holy Sepulchre, the Mount of Olives, and of course, we ate some delicious local foods. But for some reason, this place wasnâ€™t like we pictured it being.

Who are Kara and Nate?! 
Watch our documentary here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FuFv4iF8wgg&t=1s 

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are in our 9TH YEAR of finding the best adventures the world has to offer :) 

We are incredibly grateful to be able to continue doing something we love every day. ğŸ˜ŠğŸ¥ğŸŒ Thank you to everyone who has been a part of our journey!

title: WHAT IT'S LIKE INSIDE CHERNOBYL (is it safe?)
description:
Are you curious what Chernobyl looks like in 2019? Today we go inside the exclusion zone and get within a few hundred meters of reactor 4 where the explosion happened. Chernobyl is one of the most interesting and eerie places we have ever been to. It almost feels like stepping back in time. 33 years after the disaster parts of Chernobyl are still highly radioactive, but you can still visit the exclusion zone if you go with a guide who knows the areas to avoid. 

You can't visit Chernobyl without a tour guide, and we booked our tour through SoloEast. We had a great experience, and we highly recommend checking them out if you're interested in visiting Chernobyl -Â http://bit.ly/soloeast

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are in our 9TH YEAR of finding the best adventures the world has to offer :)

Who are Kara and Nate?!

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are finding the best adventures the world has to offer :) 

We are incredibly grateful to be able to continue doing something we love every day. ğŸ˜ŠğŸ¥ğŸŒ Thank you to everyone who has been a part of our journey!

title: OUR FIRST IMPRESSIONS OF MEXICO VAN LIFE
description:
Episode 817 | Baja, Mexico | Filmed March 2022

Watch our whole Baja series here: https://youtube.com/playlist?list=PLirGII1_qwvuW34iM3PE1u4GO-ynx_v1m

This video is days 4-6 of our van life road trip to the tip of the Baja peninsula! We left our beautiful cliffside campsite near Ensenada and filled up the van with diesel for the first time, ate street tacos, stocked up on popsicles, and got stopped at our first military check point. Then we headed south to Bahia de Los Angeles where we wild camped for the first time. AKA we slept on a beautiful secluded beach for FREE?! We accidentally went 3 days off the grid without internet, and by day 4 we finally made our way to a cafe to check in with our families who were worried about us ;) That's where we met our new friends, @Mrandmrsadventure â¤ï¸ Check out their channel for the ultimate 3 month Baja trip! Who are Kara and Nate?! 
Watch our documentary here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FuFv4iF8wgg&t=1s 

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are in our 9TH YEAR of finding the best adventures the world has to offer :) 

We are incredibly grateful to be able to continue doing something we love every day. ğŸ˜ŠğŸ¥ğŸŒ Thank you to everyone who has been a part of our journey!

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are in our 10TH YEAR of finding the best adventures the world has to offer :)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

title: Tokyo CAPSULE HOTEL Experience NIGHTMARE
description:

Location: A Sketchy Capsule Hotel in Tokyo, Japan

Staying at a capsule hotel was one of the things I was looking forward to most when visiting Tokyo, Japan. Our experience staying at a capsule hotel was nothing like I expected it to be.

Please don't let this video stop you from staying at a capsule hotel next time you're in Tokyo! There are much nicer hotels, but messed up and went to the wrong capsule hotel! I found a nice one on Trip Advisor, but we put the wrong address into our maps and we ended up a super gross capsule hotel. We didn't realize we had checked into the wrong hotel until it was too late! 

To stay at the capsule hotel you pay with a vending machine. We couldn't get our money back so we were stuck there for tonight. Unfortunately, they still allow smoking inside, so that didn't make our sleepless night any better. It was pretty much a nightmare experience, but we tried to make the most of it! 

If you want to know what it's like to stay at a really gross capsule hotel in Tokyo, Japan check out this VLOG!

*PLEASE read the details below if you are planning your own road trip here* :) 

Aboriginal held land in Australia is private property and to travel through, you need permission often in the form of a permit. For Kiwirrkurra Country, a permit allows you to travel along the main road, into community and camp at approved campsites. Access into any other areas aside from this is still prohibited. More information on traveling through Kiwirrkurra country can be found at https://www.tjamutjamu.com/travelling-to-kiwirrkurra-country and https://kiwirrkurra.au/. The Kiwirrkurra Traditional Owners thank you for respecting their culture and country.

ALSO! If you are looking to buy Aboriginal art, make sure you buy from the most ethical sources which are community artist-owned art galleries and collectives. For Kiwirrkurra art you can purchase through Papunya Tula Artists (https://papunyatula.com.au/). For other Central Australian Aboriginal art, visit Desart for more information at https://desart.com.au/ Thank you :)

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are finding the best adventures the world has to offer :) 

We are incredibly grateful to be able to continue doing something we love every day. ğŸ˜ŠğŸ¥ğŸŒ Thank you to everyone who has been a part of our journey!

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are finding the best adventures the world has to offer :)

title: WE STAYED WITH MONKS IN BHUTAN (a touching story)
description:
We stayed the night at a remote monastery in the mountains of Bhutan and got to spend time talking to the head monk about why he lives there with 80 children. This awesome experience was organized by Breathe Bhutan, & we highly recommend them! https://www.breathebhutan.com/

We had the opportunity to spend the night at a monastery in the middle of the Himalayan Mountains of Bhutan with no other tourist in site. The head monk there shared his emotional story with us about why he chose to live in such a remote place with over 80 monk children.

Travel vlog 689 | Country #98/100 | #Bhutan | Filmed December 6, 2019

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are in our 10TH YEAR of finding the best adventures the world has to offer :) 

We are incredibly grateful to be able to continue doing something we love every day. ğŸ˜ŠğŸ¥ğŸŒ Thank you to everyone who has been a part of our journey!

Who are Kara and Nate?! 
Watch our documentary here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FuFv4iF8wgg&t=1s 

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are in our 9TH YEAR of finding the best adventures the world has to offer :) 

We are incredibly grateful to be able to continue doing something we love every day. ğŸ˜ŠğŸ¥ğŸŒ Thank you to everyone who has been a part of our journey!

title: Halong Bay Luxury Cruise | Signature Cruise
description:
âœˆï¸  Want hidden flight deals to international destinations at up to 80% off? FareDrop is our secret weapon for finding the best deals! Try it risk free â¡ï¸  https://faredrop.app/ytd_160402 â¬…ï¸

This Halong Bay Luxury Cruise was made possible by: http://signaturehalongcruise.com/en/

If youâ€™ve never been to Halong Bay, you need to add taking a luxury cruise through Halong Bay to your bucket list! Halong Bay is a UNESCO World Heritage Site for a good reason. It is one of the most beautiful places we have ever seen! Itâ€™s filled with giant lime stone karsts that jut out of the water in every direction for miles.

The best way to experience the bay is by a luxury cruise. There are tons of cruise ship operators offering cruises through Halong Bay. The cruises range from cheap backpack boats to five start luxury cruise ships. Since visiting Halong Bay is most likely a once in a lifetime experience, we decided to splurge on a 5 star luxury cruise to ensure that we had the best experience possible!

We booked our cruise with Signature Cruise and we were elated with our experience. Seriously, we donâ€™t have a bad thing to say about Signature Cruises, and that should mean a lot coming from me because when I splurge on an experience I am very critical. Also, the staff treated us like royalty! They made our experience even better.

Our luxurious cruise through Halong Bay started with an amazing lunch served while we were cruising to a floating fishing village. After arriving at the floating village we were rowed around the village in a row boat by one of the women who lived in the floating village. After our row boat ride was completed, we visited a pearl farm to learn how pearls are made. To be completely honest, this sounded kind of lame to me when I read it on the itinerary, but it was actually really interesting!

After leaving the pearl farm, we were taken back to the cruise ship. After an hour or so of relaxing and taking in the beautiful views of Halong Bay, we had a cooking class where we learned to make fresh spring rolls. After the cooking class we enjoyed happy hour with more beautiful views. After happy hour, a delicious five course dinner was served aboard the boat. After dinner I had the opportunity to try my hand at squid fishing. I got really lucky and managed to catch 10!

If you want to know what it's like to take a luxury cruise through Halong Bay check out this VLOG!

Who are Kara and Nate?! 
Watch our documentary here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FuFv4iF8wgg&t=1s 

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are finding the best adventures the world has to offer :) 

We are incredibly grateful to be able to continue doing something we love every day. ğŸ˜ŠğŸ¥ğŸŒ Thank you to everyone who has been a part of our journey!

title: INCREDIBLE INDIAN STREET FOOD TOUR | Old Delhi's Best Street Food
description:
Food tours are our favorite things to do in new countries, and India is no different. Our new local friend Anubhav from Delhi Food Walks took us around to the BEST Indian street food spots in town!  If you go to Delhi, you MUST go on this food tour! http://delhifoodwalks.com/

This was actually a breakfast food walk, so we tried many traditional Indian breakfast foods for the first time. We stopped at 10 different places and ate Bedmi Poori with a spicy aloo sabzi and potato curry, suji halwa, sumptuous Nahari cooked overnight, Paaye or goat trotters (GOAT FEET), traditional masala chai, and SO much more!!!

Who are Kara and Nate?! 
Watch our documentary here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FuFv4iF8wgg&t=1s 

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are in our 9TH YEAR of finding the best adventures the world has to offer :) 

We are incredibly grateful to be able to continue doing something we love every day. ğŸ˜ŠğŸ¥ğŸŒ Thank you to everyone who has been a part of our journey!l

title: 36 Days Biking Across America (start to finish)
description:

title: The Maldives Soneva Fushi FULL ISLAND TOUR
description:
We don't typically say "epic," but we couldn't think of a better word to describe this day! Thank you Soneva Fushi! https://www.soneva.com/soneva-fushi/#experiences Today we woke up in our dreamy villa and rode our bikes to the breakfast buffet on the beach. It was overwhelmingly delicious! Next our very own "Mr. Friday" gave us a tour of the whole island via golf cart. It ended at Soneva Fushi's private yacht where we jumped off 7 meters into the ocean! We then took a boat to our VERY OWN ISLAND! They packed us a cooler and a cell phone and left us on the most beautiful tiny island with only an umbrella and overwater hammock! It was raining and cloudy when they dropped us off, but thankfully it cleared up so we quickly frolicked along the beach and flew the drone, and it went by WAY too fast! Next, we grabbed a quick lunch which just happened to include a buffet of my favorite food - SUSHI! And then we ride 25 minutes via speedboat to a snorkeling spot with the island's marine biologist (YEP). It was the bluest, warmest, clearest water we've ever been in, and we saw sea turtles and huge sting rays! After that we got on ANOTHER boat for a dolphin sunset sail complete with champagne and gourmet snacks. We watched Spinner Dolphins play while the sun went down behind them, and IT WAS THE MOST MAGICAL DAY OF OUR LIVES :)

title: AMERICAN FOOTBALL VS. EUROPEAN FOOTBALL (We Went to the Biggest Rivalry Games)
description:
We flew to Spain to answer this question: American Football vs. European "Soccer" - which is better?! We found out by going to the biggest rivalry game on both continents: Real Madrid vs. Barcelona âš½ï¸ & Tennessee Vols vs. Florida Gators ğŸˆ The two experiences were WAY different than we expected! Which sport do you prefer?! Special thanks to Rocket Learn for sponsoring this episode! Check out the latest episode of Home Lore here:Â https://youtu.be/PpZmD_5Le0A 

We grew up watching American Football and have always wanted to go to a "soccer" game (calling it soccer to prevent confusion ;)). 

The Tennessee Vols and Florida Gators have been rival teams for awhile now, and Tennessee is actually good this year, so we thought that'd be a great game to go watch in real life.

Then we learned that Real Madrid and Barcelona were going to be playing each other (AKA El Clasico!) WHILE we were in Spain! 

We had the best time sharing game day at our alma mater, AND getting to experience our very first "soccer" game with our new friend Yoanna!

At the end of the day, even though these 2 sports are very different from each other, our favorite part was seeing people (and complete strangers) from all over the world at both events bonding, putting their differences aside, and having a great time together :) 

Did any of our comparisons surprise you? Comment below annd let us know which experience youd prefer :)

Who are Kara and Nate?!

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are finding the best adventures the world has to offer :) 

We are incredibly grateful to be able to continue doing something we love every day. ğŸ˜ŠğŸ¥ğŸŒ Thank you to everyone who has been a part of our journey!

Who are Kara and Nate?! 

2016-2019: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FuFv4iF8wgg&t=1s 

2020-2024: https://youtu.be/ikAN9e0gBaU?si=G644UGWIqPrOzTYW

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are in our 9TH YEAR of finding the best adventures the world has to offer :) 

We are incredibly grateful to be able to continue doing something we love every day. ğŸ˜ŠğŸ¥ğŸŒ Thank you to everyone who has been a part of our journey!

Who are Kara and Nate?!

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are finding the best adventures the world has to offer :) 

We are incredibly grateful to be able to continue doing something we love every day. ğŸ˜ŠğŸ¥ğŸŒ Thank you to everyone who has been a part of our journey!

Who are Kara and Nate?! 

2016-2019: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FuFv4iF8wgg&t=1s  

2020-2024: https://youtu.be/ikAN9e0gBaU?si=G644UGWIqPrOzTYW 

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are in our 10TH YEAR of finding the best adventures the world has to offer :) 

We are incredibly grateful to be able to continue doing something we love every day. ğŸ˜ŠğŸ¥ğŸŒ Thank you to everyone who has been a part of our journey!

title: WE SWAM BETWEEN CONTINENTAL PLATES! (Snorkeling Silfra: Iceland travel vlog)
description:
Thank you Nordic Holidays! Book your Silfra trip here! https://www.icelandontheweb.com/tour/item/1023/into-the-blue-snorkelling-silfra
We drove to Thingvellir National Park to a rift called Silfra which is a fissure between the North American and Eurasion tectonic plates. The water is nearly freezing, but we swam in it for an hour! Wearing drysuits for the first time was a fun experience and made the snorkel trip so much better. The water was unbelievably clear. This was definitely one of the best adventures we took in Iceland!!!

Originally from Nashville, Tennessee, we got married 2013 and were super â€œnormal.â€ I was a teacher and Nate started a small printing business from the spare bedroom of our apartment. 

We discovered the world of â€œtravel hackingâ€ while planning our honeymoon & became addicted ;)

So after 2 years of obsessively saving $35k and over 2 million miles and points, we sold our cars and apartment and left home January 10, 2016 for a â€œone yearâ€ trip around the world.

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are in our 10TH YEAR of finding the best adventures the world has to offer :) 

We are incredibly grateful to be able to continue doing something we love every day. ğŸ˜ŠğŸ¥ğŸŒ Thank you to everyone who has been a part of our journey!

Our goal was to see as many places as possible before we ran out of money and went back home to â€œnormal life.â€ We started this channel to share our experiences with friends and family, but quickly fell in love with living on the road and found a new passion for capturing our travels through video. So we did everything we could to keep going.

4 years later, we achieved our new goal of visiting 100 countries and all 7 continents. We had no plans to slow down, until 2020 forced us to ;) Which is when we bought a converted van to start exploring our own country for the first time!

After ~2 years of van life, we are back to full time international traveling! And now we are in our 10TH YEAR of finding the best adventures the world has to offer :) 

We are incredibly grateful to be able to continue doing something we love every day. ğŸ˜ŠğŸ¥ğŸŒ Thank you to everyone who has been a part of our journey!

title: LUXOR TEMPLE & VALLEY OF THE KINGS | Egypt Travel Vlog
description:
We only had one day to explore Luxor, Egypt, so even though we barely slept on the overnight train from Cairo, we went out at 7:00 A.M. to be the first and only tourists at the incredible Luxor Temple! It was totally worth it because it wasn't too hot yet and we took all the videos and photos we wanted with NO other people! Once the first tour bus arrived, we headed back to our hotel and had breakfast (AND COFFEE), but then decided to nap for few hours to wait out the mid day heat before heading to the Valley of the Kings via a $0.10 ferry and $7 taxi. Once again, we felt like there should have been way more tourists than there was, but we weren't complaining!

title: EATING BUGS in Cambodia!
description:
âœˆï¸  Want hidden flight deals to international destinations at up to 80% off? FareDrop is our secret weapon for finding the best deals! Try it risk free â¡ï¸  https://faredrop.app/ytd_160223 â¬…ï¸

We NEVER in our wildest dreams thought we'd find our selves eating bugs in the streets of Cambodia. Travel has a way of making you crave new experience, and eating a tarantula and scorpion was definitely a new experience from us.

A few of the street food vendors in Cambodia have giant plates of bugs for sale. While we were there, we didn't see any other tourist eating the bugs, so when we decided to eat a scorpion and a tarantula, it drew a crowd.

The man selling the bugs warmed us up with a cricket. Then, we tried the scorpion. I tried to stop us there, but kara basically forced me to eat the spider!     

If you want to see our reactions to eating the bugs, check out this VLOG!

title: SUMO WRESTLING Tournament | Tokyo, Japan
description:
âœˆï¸  We created an app to help you save up to 80% on international flights! Try it risk free  â¡ï¸  https://faredrop.app/ytd_160115 â¬…ï¸

SUMO WRESTLING Tournament | Tokyo, Japan
Location: Sumo Stadium - Tokyo, Japan

Watching a sumo wrestling tournament was our most memorable experience from our trip to Tokyo! We spent an entire day watching the tournament. The rituals before an after each match are as much a part of the sumo experience as the wrestling itself. 

The rituals get even more elaborate later in the day when the Makuuchi (Grand Sumo Champions) matches begin! There is an elaborate ceremony to introduce the Grand Sumo Champions, and the rituals before their matches are much longer.

I was very surprised by the size difference in many of the wrestlers. There are not weight class in sumo wrestling. Also, the sumo wrestlers in the morning matches were much smaller than the better wrestlers who wrestle later in the day! 

If you go to a sumo wrestling tournament at Ryogoku Kokugikan Stadium, expect it to be very empty during the morning matches. Don't worry, once the after noon wrestling matches begin, the crowd begins to poor in and the stadium becomes electric during the grand sumo matches.

If you want to know what it's like to attend a Sumo Wrestling Tournament in Tokyo, Japan check out this VLOG!

We'd like to say thanks to +blackarmy81 who posted the following video that inspired us to visit a sumo wrestling match -  Sumo Wrestling 2014 05 21 Tokyo Japan - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZCiJH...

We also have to give thanks to GuillaumeErard.com for their their inspiring video - Summer Grand Sumo Tournament Final Highlights (Tokyo - 20 May 2012) - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lRuQB...

title: FIRST IMPRESSIONS OF CANADA | Vancouver Travel Vlog
description:
Enter our 400k Giveaway here :) https://karaandnate.com/400k-giveaway/ GOOD LUCK! WE ARE SO GRATEFUL FOR ALL OF YOU!!!

We had NO IDEA how awesome Vancouver, Canada is! Great food, Asian influence, strong coffee, kind people, and today it was all topped off with beautiful fall weather! GET $35 OFF YOUR FIRST AIRBNB STAY:
https://www.airbnb.com/c/karab49

Our cute AirBnb Apartment in this video: https://www.airbnb.com/rooms/13773521
----------------
When grocery shopping in Cape Town, a woman was mugged right in front of us. Honestly, I'm surprised after how much we've travelled that we haven't seen one before. It was a very scary experience to see, I can't imagine if it actually happened to us. It was in the middle of the day with people all around. The woman was not physically harmed, and we do not know if they ever caught the man who attacked her. It was a wake up call for us though, since we always walk around with a camera, phones, and bags. Dangerous happenings are everywhere and not just in Cape Town, so we are definitely going to be more cautious of our surroundings. 
--------------------- 
We got settled in to our sweet as AirBnb apartment in the middle of Cape Town, then got lunch at Skinny Legs and some groceries for the week. We ended the day with our new favorite hike to the top of Lion's Head for the sunset!

title: BUNGY JUMP Queenstown, New Zealand | Nevis & Kawarau Bridge
description:
âœˆï¸ @DailyDrop is our FREE travel newsletter! Get all the best travel news, tips, and tricks every weekday in your inbox by subscribing here â¡ï¸
https://www.dailydrop.com/sign-up?utm_source=karaandnate&utm_medium=youtube&utm_campaign=yt%20karaandnate 

ğŸ“¸ Follow us on Instagram for behind the scenes content: @karaandnate https://www.instagram.com/karaandnate/ 

 ğŸŒ We created Daily Drop Pro to help you score super cheap travel with cash or points! Try it risk free and get flight deals up to 80% off â¡ï¸ 
https://www.dailydrop.com/pro?utm_source=karaandnate&utm_medium=youtube&utm_campaign=yt%20karaandnate

Bungy jumping in Queenstown, New Zealand has been the highlight of our time in New Zealand. In this vlog you'll see two of Queenstown's most popular bungy jumps, the Nevis Bungy Jump and the Kawarau Bridge Bungy Jump. Both bungy jumps are owned by the AJ Hackett company. They are professionally run, and we felt safe and sound in their hands... sort of. At least as much as you can feel safe while bungee jumping!

We started off our morning in Queenstown with Jordan and Julianne jumping from Kawarau Bridge Bungy Jump. This jump is 43 meters high. It was the first bungy jump to be established in New Zealand. The scenery is absolutely beautiful, and you jump in to the turquoise water of the glacial river below! 

Kara and I jumped from the Nevis Bungy Jump later that afternoon. The Nevis Bungy is 3 times taller than the Kawarau Bridge Bungy. For this jump you ride a little metal cart out to a small building that's hanging between two mountains. Then you jump from 134 meters above the ground. This is the tallest bungy jump in New Zealand and the 14th tallest in the world! 

If you want to know what it's like to jump from the highest bungy jump in New Zealand check out this VLOG!

title: EATING delicious street food in Singapore's Chinatown
description:
âœˆï¸  Check out the travel app we created that helps you find incredibly cheap flights to the amazing destinations all over the world! Try it risk free â¡ï¸  https://faredrop.app/ytd_160131 â¬…ï¸

Location: Chinatown, Singapore. 

Eating at Chinatown in Singapore is an experience that shouldn't be missed when visiting Singapore! The food court in Chinatown is filled with a dizzying number of delicious food options. During this excursion we choose to try fried carrot cake, chili crab dumplings, and ice kacang also know as Malaysian shaved iced.

All the food we tried was amazing! Our trip to Chinatown was made even more exciting because the town was decorated for Chinese New Year. The streets where packed with people, but the atmosphere was fantastic. We would highly recommend visiting Chinatown during Chinese New Years.

We want to say a special thanks to Kyle Le Dot Net who inspired this food excursion to Chinatown with his video: eating at a Singapore FOOD COURT in CHINATOWN

title: BEST Indian food in Kuala Lumpur!
description:

Location: Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia

Are looking for an authentic foodie experience in Kuala Lumpur? Look no further than this amazing banana leaf restaurant in Little Indian. Based on +mark wiens recommendation, we visited Kuala Lumpur's best Indian restaurant, Vishalatchi Food and Catering.

This was by far the best meal we had in Kuala Lumpur. We aren't accustom to eating with our hands or off banana leaves, but the staff was more than happy to teach us the proper way!

If you consider yourself a foodie, and you find yourself in Kuala Lumpur, you shouldn't miss the opportunity to eat at my favorite restaurant in Kuala Lumpur - Vishalatchi Food and Catering!

If you want to know what it's like to visit a banana leaf restaurant in Kuala Lumpur check out this VLOG!

title: DELICIOUS Thai Street Food at Chiang Maiâ€™s Sunday Night Market
description:
âœˆï¸  Want hidden flight deals to international destinations at up to 80% off? FareDrop is our secret weapon for finding the best deals! Try it risk free â¡ï¸  https://faredrop.app/ytd_160308 â¬…ï¸

Location: Chiang Mai, Thailand Sunday Night Market

Visiting the Chiang Mai Sunday Night Market is an experience that shouldnâ€™t be missed! If youâ€™re planning a trip to Chiang Mai Thailand, make sure that youâ€™re here on a Sunday Night. The market is HUGE, and full of tons of delicious food. 



The night market literally stretches for almost 2km. We spent hours wandering the streets, and we still couldnâ€™t see the end of the market when we gave up! This night market in Chiang Mai is better than any other night market weâ€™ve been to in Thailand! 



The Sunday Night Market had an amazing selection of local goods. Even though there are thousands of stalls that set up on Sunday nights in Chiang Mai, very few of them sell the same thing. A pleasant surprise after visiting the night markets of Bangkok.



If you want to know what it's like to visit the Chiang Mai Sunday Night Market, check out this VLOG!

title: Learning to eat INDIAN FOOD in Singapore's Little India
description:
âœˆï¸  We created an app to help you save up to 80% on international flights! Try it risk free  â¡ï¸  https://faredrop.app/ytd_160201 â¬…ï¸

Location: Little India, Singapore

Today we ventured to Singapore's Little India to enjoy some delicious Indian food! Before we started traveling, we never ate Indian food. Little did we know what we were missing out on. Little Indian in Singapore was the perfect place to experience authentic meal of Indian Food.

We ducked into a local Indian restaurant where we were the only tourist. We ordered some things that sounded kinda familiar, but when the food arrived, we realized we had to no clue how to properly eat Indian food.

The Indian man running the restaurant took us under his wing, and showed us how to eat with our hands. He was very picky about our form, which we both thought was funny. We learned how to properly push the food into our mouths using our thumbs.

If you want to know what it's like eating indian food in Singapore's Little India check out this VLOG!

title: JORDAN Travel Vlog | Jesus Was Baptized HERE (Jerash & Mt. Nebo)
description:
We spent the last 2 days on a road trip through Jordan exploring some of the most fascinating historical sites this country is home to. We had no idea the amount of incredible sites we would see on this trip, including: the ancient city of Jarash (most well-preserved city outside of Italy), Jesus's baptism site on the Jordan river (where we were about 20 feet away from Israel), Mt. Nebo (where God showed Moses the Promised Land), and SO MUCH MORE. Of course lots of delicious Jordanian food was involved. We ended the day at the Dead Sea where we will float tomorrow. :)

title: Swimming with WHALE SHARKS in Oslob, Cebu Philippines
description:
âœˆï¸  We created FareDrop to help you score super cheap international flights! Try it risk free and get flight deals up to 80% off  â¡ï¸  https://faredrop.app/ytd_160122 â¬…ï¸

Location: Oslob, Cebu Philippines

Get $40+ off your first AirBnB stay through our link!: 
https://www.airbnb.com/c/karaw76/

If you are visiting the island of Cebu, swimming with the whale sharks in Oslob is a MUST-DO experience. Oslob Cebu is one of the best and most consistent places to swim with Whale Sharks. Since the fishermen of Oslob feed the whale sharks daily, they come back every day. If you pay for the snorkeling you are almost guaranteed to see whale sharks!

On the day that we went on the snorkeling tour there were nine whale sharks! We got to encounter four of these gentle giants while we were in the water!

The biggest draw back to the entire whale shark experience is the crowds of people. Since Oslob has become know as for this tourist attraction, hoards of people flock to the beach every morning to swim with the whale sharks.

If you want to know what it's like to swim with a 25 foot whale shark, check out this video!

We'd like to say thanks to Just One Way Ticket for the inspiring video "Snorkeling with Whale Sharks in Oslob Philippines [ GoPro Hero 3+ Black ]" that lead us to Oslob!

We also have to give thanks to @GoPro and their inspiring video Gopro: whale shark dive in the Philippines

title: DON'T go to SUNRISE at ANGKOR WAT!
description:
âœˆï¸  We created an app to help you save up to 80% on international flights! Try it risk free  â¡ï¸  https://faredrop.app/ytd_160222 â¬…ï¸

Location: Angkor Wat, Siem Reap, Cambodia. 

This morning we woke up at 4 a.m. to see the sunrise at Angkor Wat. It was OK... To be completely honest, I think there are much better ways to spend your morning exploring the Angkor Temple complex.

Sunrise at Angkor Wat is OVERRUN by tourist. Yes, we did contribute to the problem, but that's beside the point. When we showed up to Angkor Wat at 5 a.m. there were already TONS of people there. We weren't even able to get a seat on the far side of the pond. By the time the sun was rising, there were over 2,000 people watching the sunrise with us. The crowds were almost more impressive than the sunrise.

Don't get me wrong, the sunrise over Angkor Wat is beautiful, but so is everything else at the Angkor Temple complex. I would suggest getting up super early one day an visiting other temples besides Angkor Wat at around 6 a.m.. You could have the amazing temples to yourself while everyone else is fighting at Angkor Wat to snap the best picture of the sunrise.

title: Moscow Market & FIRST TASTE OF RUSSIAN FOOD!
description:
Want to know all of the details about visas, booking your tickets, etc.? We created the Ultimate Guide to Riding the Trans-Siberian Railway! Read it here http://karaandnate.com/the-ultimate-guide-to-riding-the-trans-siberian-railway/

They weren't easy to order, but totally worth the effort!

title: TWO SIDES OF ST. LUCIA! 15 Day Repositioning Cruise
description:
Thanks Windjammer for helping us out! http://www.windjammer-landing.com/ // The beautiful island of St. Lucia is our 65th country and 4th stop on this repositioning cruise from England to Barbados. We had a catamaran tour booked and planned to spend the whole day out in the sunshine circling the island. Unfortunately that plan fell through at the last minute, but instead we had an incredible day hanging out with locals at the market, eating the national dish, and then spending a beautiful afternoon at an all-inclusive resort flying the drone and laying in over-water hammocks! Not a bad plan B :)

title: Hanoi Old Quarter | CRAZY Cheap North Face!
description:
âœˆï¸  We created FareDrop to help you score super cheap international flights! Try it risk free and get flight deals up to 80% off  â¡ï¸  https://faredrop.app/ytd_160329.1 â¬…ï¸

Location: Hanoi Old Quarter
New Facebook Page - https://www.facebook.com/karaandnate/

Visiting the Old Quarter in Hanoi was by far my favorite activity in Hanoi, Vietnam! I could literally just walk around the old quarter for weeks without getting board. While walking around the old quarter in Hanoi you constantly have to dodge motor bikes! It really keeps you on your toes.

You never know what you're going to see when walking around the old quarter. One second you might see chickens playing in the road. The next minute you'll see hundreds of knock off Rolex watches. One thing that I guarantee you'll see TONS of stores selling cheap North Face apparel.

Apparently North Face apparel in Hanoi is cheap because the North Face factory is located in Vietnam? I don't know how true this is, but I do know that Kara scored a nice "North Face" puffy jacket for only $20 in the Old Quarter of Hanoi in a store called Made in Vietnam!

If you want to know what it's like visiting Hanoi's Old Quarter check out this VLOG!

title: Halong Bay Luxury Cruise | Day 2
description:
âœˆï¸  We created FareDrop to help you score super cheap international flights! Try it risk free and get flight deals up to 80% off  â¡ï¸  https://faredrop.app/ytd_160403 â¬…ï¸

This Halong Bay Luxury Cruise was made possible by: http://signaturehalongcruise.com/en/

Watch Day 1 of Halong Bay Luxury Cruise with Signature Halong Cruise - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3N1ppVq_yNk

Day 2 of our luxurious cruise through Halong Bay started with an early morning thai chi lesson. We learned to do Thai Chi on the top of the cruise ship while we cruised past the beautiful karsts that fill Halong Bay. After our class we were served a light breakfast before getting on the smaller boat to visit a cave inside one of the limestone karsts.

We left for the cave at 7 a.m.. Thankfully, Signature Cruises makes it a point to get there early. By the time we had finished exploring the cave, a lot more cruise ships had showed up. The cave was packed with tourists! We were lucky to get to experience the cave with only a few other people there.

After visiting the cave we had the opportunity to kayak back to the ship. We took the long way back and circled the island that held the cave. Being in a kayak so low to the water really helped us to appreciate the massive size of the limestone mountains that jut out of the water.

After returning the ship, we were served a delicious brunch as we cruised back to the port. Sadly, shortly after finishing brunch we arrived back to the port where we had to disembark the cruise ship. It was sad saying bye to ship and the amazing staff. Our only regret is that we didn't book a longer cruise!

If you want to know what it's like to take a luxury cruise through Halong Bay check out this VLOG!

Thanks for watching! If you want to follow our adventure, you can do so using any of the social media links below!

title: Cathay Pacific Wing FIRST CLASS Lounge HKG
description:

Location: Cathay Pacific "The Wing" First Class Lounge, HKG Airport, Hong Kong.

The Cathay Pacific "The Wing" First Class Lounge is known around the world for having the nicest bathroom of any airline lounge! They call these lounges "relaxation cabanas". Visitors to the lounge are allowed up to 1 hour and 30 minutes to enjoy the relaxation cabanas. You can have a nice long soak in the bath tub to relax before your next flight!

Additionally, "The Wing" first class lounge has a full service restaurant complete with a buffet sushi bar! Last but not least there is a champagne bar that features several varieties of high end champagne.

After we had spent several hours enjoying The Wing, we decided to head over an check out Cathay Pacific other first class lounge "The Pier". We specially visited this lounge because they give complementary foot massages! Unfortunately, we didn't have time to get one before boarding our flight.

If you want to know what it's like to spent a day in the HKG Cathay Pacific Wing First Class lounges check out this VLOG!

After watching the @inflightexpert's video, Cathay Pacific FIRST CLASS | New CX FIRST - HKG to ICN | 1080[HD] Flight Experience, we were even more excited to visit The Wing!

title: Cruising the PANAMA CANAL (full transit time lapse)
description:
Taking a cruise through the Panama Canal is the coolest way to experience this historical and fascinating waterway. Make sure you watch through the end to see the whole Panama Canal time lapse without interruption! :) This was our 9th day on our portion of MSC's around the world cruise. We left the ship and did a small boat cruise down the second have of the canal, and the next day we passed through the entire canal from the Atlantic side to the Pacific side of Panama on the cruise ship (MSC Magnifica).

Travel vlog 595 | Panama Canal, Panama | Country #86/100 | Filmed January 2019

description:

title: Landing on the SHORTEST RUNWAY in the  WORLD! Flying to Saba Island
description:
The tiny island of Saba is home to the world's shortest commercial runway. It is 400 meters long with jagged cliffs on all sides. So since we were only a 15 minute flight away in St. Martin, we HAD to see it for ourselves! I am terrified of small planes, but Nate convinced me it was an experience we wouldn't regret ;)

title: DELICIOUS Vietnamese Coffee | Egg Coffee | Coconut Coffee
description:
âœˆï¸  We created an app to help you save up to 80% on international flights! Try it risk free  â¡ï¸  https://faredrop.app/ytd_160401 â¬…ï¸

If you've watched any of our vlogs you know we LOVE coffee! Vietnamese coffee is our new favorite coffee! Neither one of us had ever had egg coffee or coconut coffee. We had no idea what we've been missing out on our whole lives! 

We searched the city of Hanoi for at least an hour looking for a cafe that served egg coffee. We finally found a local cafe that served amazing egg coffee! We had no clue what to expect, but we didn't know how much the taste, flavor, and texture would blow us away! 

Egg coffee is like nothing we have ever had before! It's a raw egg that is whipped and added to vietnamese coffee. The result is the creamiest most delicious froth we have ever tasted! 

Coconut coffee is completely different, but we might have enjoyed it even more! It's basically a combination of a coconut smoothie, vietnamese coffee, and sweetened condensed milk. I think I would live in Vietnam just to drink this amazing coffee every morning! 

If you want to know what it's like drinking Vietnamese coffee in the Old Quarter of Hanoi check out this VLOG!

title: Cathay Pacific Pier FIRST CLASS Lounge HKG
description:
âœˆï¸  We created an app to help you save up to 80% on international flights! Try it risk free  â¡ï¸  https://faredrop.app/ytd_160213.1 â¬…ï¸

Location: Cathay Pacific Pier First Class Lounge

The Cathay Pacific Pier First Class Lounge is one of two first class lounges in the HKG airport. The other first class lounge is the Cathay Pacific "Wing First Class Lounge". Last time we were at the HKG airport we spent most of our time at The Wing.

This time, we spent the majority of the time enjoying "The Pier". The Wing get a lot of recognition because of it's "relaxation cabanas" and champagne bar, but I think The Pier is a superior lounge!

The Pier offer a much wider menu at the sit-down restaurant, and you can get a free foot massage or back massage! Next time you're in the HKG airport, make sure to set some time aside for visiting The Pier. Also, make sure to put your name in early for a massage!

If you want to know what it's like to visit the Cathay Pacific Pier First Class Lounge in HKG check out this VLOG!

title: 24 HOURS on the SMALLEST ISLAND in the Caribbean | Saba Travel Vlog
description:
The Island of Saba in the Caribbean is so unique that when we heard about it, we just had to go see it for ourselves! It is home to the shortest commercial runway in the world (400 meters), and has the highest point in the Kingdom of the Netherlands. We were only here for 24 hours, but we made the most of it and hiked to the very top to be the highest people in all of the Netherlands and see spectacular views of the island!

title: BEST Vietnamese Sandwich in Hanoi | Banh Mi
description:
âœˆï¸  Want hidden flight deals to international destinations at up to 80% off? FareDrop is our secret weapon for finding the best deals! Try it risk free â¡ï¸  https://faredrop.app/ytd_160329 â¬…ï¸

Want to know where you can find the best Vietnamese Sandwich in Hanoi? Perhaps in the WHOLE WORLD? Banh Mi 25 in the Old Quarter of Hanoi severs up the best Vietnamese sandwiches we've ever had! Nate's favorite is the honey chicken banh mi sandwich. Kara LOVED the veggie and cheese sandwich.

In addition to severing the best vietnamese sandwiches in Hanoi, the family that runs Bahn Mi 25 are some of the nicest people you'll ever meet! The owner (I don't know his name) spent 20 minutes talking to us and sharing his passion for home country! He genuinely wants more people to experience joy in home city of Vietnam!

Also, even though the sandwiches are only around $1 USD, the give you free tea and bananas! You really can't beat this place! If you're in Hanoi don't miss your chance to eat at Banh Mi 25!

If you want to know what it's like to eat the best vietnamese sandwich in Hanoi, check out this VLOG!

title: TEMPLE STREET Night Market | Hong Kong's BEST Night Market
description:
âœˆï¸  Want hidden flight deals to international destinations at up to 80% off? FareDrop is our secret weapon for finding the best deals! Try it risk free â¡ï¸  https://faredrop.app/ytd_160206 â¬…ï¸

Location: Temple Street Night Market, Hong Kong

The Temple Street Night Market is Hong Kong's biggest and best night market! Make sure to plan a trip to the night market on your next visit to Hong Kong! It's a great way to take in the culture of Hong Kong in and around the market. The market is four full blocks of street stalls selling everything from selfie sticks to hand painted Chinese fans. 

If you're like us and mostly visit night markets for their food, I have bad new for you. None of the stalls in the night market serve food. The Temple Street is totally devoted to shopping. However, just a block away is the Ladies Market. This night market is know for selling fresh fruits, vegetables, and meats. If you prefer not to cook your own food, you can check out one of the many restaurants located on the streets adjacent to the Temple Street Night Market. Even if you're not into into shopping, we still highly recommend visiting the night market to get a feel for the streets of Hong Kong.

If you want to know what it's like to visit the Temple Street Night Market check out this VLOG starting at 8:11!

We'd like to say thanks to @AndyandMeesh for their inspiration to visit to the Temple Street Night Market. Check out their video

title: FIRST DAYS IN BEAUTIFUL BALI | Canggu & Tanah Lot Temple by Scooter
description:
Our first two days in Bali, Indonesia were amazing! Nate surfed in Canggu, and we rented a scooter to drive to the Tanah Lot Temple at sunrise. It's a temple on a rock formation in the ocean, and we were the only tourists getting to watch the Hindu ceremonies the locals were starting their day with! Next we got a "local" DELICIOUS smoothie bowl (which turns out is not overrated at all), and a authentic "Warung" meal. We ended the day with our new friends Jordan, Olivia, and Richard! Taking the bus from Siem Reap to Bangkok is an "experience". This was our first overland border crossing, and our first time taking local bus in Cambodia and Thailand. The trip didn't exactly make for a fun day, but looking back it wasn't that bad. If you're looking for a cheap way to get from Siem Reap to Bangkok, and you have time to kill, consider taking the buses.

title: First Day in Tbilisi, Georgia | NOT WHAT WE EXPECTED!
description:

title: The ICONIC Petronas Towers | Kuala Lumpur
description:
